  "titleEn": "Alert in Mobile Marketplace: 26 fraudulent applications detected attempting to steal digital asset keys",
  "summaryEn": "Technical investigators have identified a group of malicious applications in a prominent mobile marketplace that impersonate popular digital wallets. The goal of this attack is to capture recovery phrases and private keys to steal digital assets.",
  "contentEn": "<p>A recent finding by technical investigators has put the community of digital asset users on high alert. The presence of at least 26 fraudulent applications has been confirmed in a major mobile marketplace, operating under the guise of well-known digital wallets. The primary objective of this sophisticated fraud scheme is the theft of digital assets through the capture of sensitive information.</p><h2>The deception mechanism: redirection and impersonation</h2><p>The method used by these applications is particularly insidious. Once a user downloads and launches the application, it not only mimics the interface of a known wallet but also redirects the user to web pages designed to appear legitimate. These fraudulent pages request the entry of the recovery phrase (seed phrase) and private keys under the pretext of a supposed update or safety verification necessary for the service to be functional.</p><h3>A latent danger in the mobile ecosystem</h3><p>According to technical reports, these malicious applications have been circulating in the mobile application store since at least the autumn of 2025. The ability of these apps to bypass safety protocols raises critical questions regarding the effectiveness of review processes against highly targeted social engineering threats designed for financial identity theft.</p><h2>How to protect your digital assets</h2><p>Given this scenario, experts recommend extreme caution when managing digital wallets on mobile devices. It is essential to always verify the developer's identity before any download and, most importantly, never enter the recovery phrase into any web page or application that is not a local and known interface of trusted software. The golden rule in the digital asset world remains in effect: your recovery phrase is your only defense and must never be shared in external digital environments.</p>"
}
